				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mrwrong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2039383); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2039383&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183506" alt="MrWrong" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2039383)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mrwrong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2039383); return false;" >MrWrong</a></span> <span class="odate time_1493170197 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Apr 2017 01:29</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2801722">
									

<p>Like I said during a critique, this feels quite interesting for one reason. IJAMEA, like all apparatus of Imperial Japan, should have died down after the war. It normally won't have such influence into the 21st century (to the point of a base in China, of all things), and yet they do. It brings into question as to how active they still are in the modern era, that not even Japan's defeat in WWII has stopped their drive.</p>
<p>While unaddressed here, it begs to ask what kind of methods they resorted to in order to outlast the postwar years that deliberately dismantled Japanese imperialism and raised a generation of militarism-adverse Japanese?</p>
<p>Overall, this helps to give IJAMEA some shelf life outside of the Imperial Japan era.</p>
<p>P.S. I think I can crosslink SCP-2511 to yours. I just need to figure out the proper place.</p>

							</div>

								
