		<div class="post" id="post-2805743">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2805743)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2805743">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fumeinadebaisu" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2831477); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2831477&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183506" alt="fumeinadebaisu" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2831477)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fumeinadebaisu" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2831477); return false;" >fumeinadebaisu</a></span> <span class="odate time_1493522019 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Apr 2017 03:13</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2805743">
									

<blockquote>
<p>IJAMEA, like all apparatus of Imperial Japan, should have died down after the war. It normally won't have such influence into the 21st century (to the point of a base in China, of all things), and yet they do. It brings into question as to how active they still are in the modern era, that not even Japan's defeat in WWII has stopped their drive.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I've been working on a <a href="http://scpsandbox2.wikidot.com/fumeinadebaisu" target="_blank">draft</a> that was for the history contest but apparently late. This is centered around an anomalous community in modern Japan, but also mentions IJAMEA in its pre-history. In it I tried (and am trying) to justify co-existence of IJAMEA, Shūshū-In (JP GoI, an anomalous agency of Imperial Japan) and Yōkai batallion.</p>
<p>FYI, <a href="https://twitter.com/Chysophylax/status/819182774665916416" target="_blank">many of JP member (30% in this survey) think Shūshū-In, IJAMEA, Onmyōryō and Unit Negative Numbers (an anomalous IJA agency superficially dedicated to study anomalous war technology) can co-exist in a same timeline</a>.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-688044-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-688044-1')">1</a></sup> Collision happening here is that Shūshū-In would be dismantled in 1945, and most of surviving personnel were hired by the Foundation or GOC, amnesticized to send back to general population or terminated. Few dissidents managed to evade those fates and formed often-namesake groups, many of them hostile.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">SPOILER!!!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>It's basically about ambition and finesse of Ashifune. He utilized IJA to gain power in Shūshū-In. Unit Negative Numbers' purpose was to create super soldiers, but it was actually for his pursuit of immortality. At the latest in the 1944, he betrayed his country and groups, approached to the Foundation, and make a bargain to be acquitted of his past seizure of objects and assume some good position in the Foundation after collapse of the Imperial-military regime. Eventually assassinated on August 16, 1945, he was reincarnated as Agent Kanahebi, and later became the Director of Site-9█.</p>
<p>Mostly from <a href="http://ja.scp-wiki.net/agent-kanahebi-s-personnal-file" target="_blank">Agent Kanahebi's personal file (Japanese)</a> since Unit Negative Numbers has barely GoI-worthy number of articles, and Shūshū-In's mainly focused to contemporary 'dissidents' activities, with only fragmented past information. It's also worth noting that the Ashifune-Kanahebi identity plot is not obviously written.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>I'm not so inclined to perfectly unify the canon around this, though. I just hope this will give some more depth and new perspective.</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-688044-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-688044-1')">1</a>. 29% say they have some special relation inter-universe, 23% answered they don't know enough about these groups, and 18% deny co-existence.</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
