<p>Thank you for the extreme details here. I am sure that this information would be of benefit, especially when looking at how the foreign language sites work their stories.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Apart from this, Shushu-In being relatively free from the Imperial Japanese government seems rather popular as a headcanon.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Notable bit of information here.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Utilizing anomalous spaces, just like Yokai Yokocho, as shelters and/or secret HQs.<br />
Hiding in remote and low-level population areas, as of SCP-824-1.<br />
Hiding entrances for hideouts, hideouts themselves, or personnel with anti-memetic technology.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>All are indeed very promising options for stories in both here and JP site, I feel.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>幻島同盟 (The Confederate Island Countries of Phantom)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>If you may pardon me, personally, I would translate that as 'The League/Union/Alliance<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-805972-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-805972-1')">1</a></sup> of Phantom Islands'. The Confederation Island Countries of Phantom implies that the country can be called 'Phantom' (in the same way as People's Republic of China can be called China).</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-805972-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-805972-1')">1</a>. 同盟 translates to these three, according to jisho.com. That being said,<br />
I leave it to your judgment regarding which would be optimal.</div>
</div>

