		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2805564)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2805564">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fumeinadebaisu" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2831477); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2831477&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183506" alt="fumeinadebaisu" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2831477)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fumeinadebaisu" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2831477); return false;" >fumeinadebaisu</a></span> <span class="odate time_1493504110 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Apr 2017 22:15</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2805564">
									

<p>Wow, a GoI format for IJAMEA! At last.</p>
<p>But then, for my Japanese-native eyes the typeface of the logo is too arid, and a bit feels like anachronism.</p>
<p><sub>And in Japan, it's hard to convince people you're doing cool things if they have MS gothic from hell in their visual design.</sub></p>
<p>Imperial Japanese military organizations generally don't have insignias like Western counterparts outside flags, so a text logo is not a poor choice, but since brush calligraphy is widely used in such cases, it would be far better and realistic, and looks serious if it is done with gorgeous, glorious brush-written style.<br />
ex. <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Japanese_calligraphy_logos">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Japanese_calligraphy_logos</a> <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:RITSUMEIKAN_Wooden_Plaque_by_Prince_Saionji_(Kyoto,_Japan).JPG">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:RITSUMEIKAN_Wooden_Plaque_by_Prince_Saionji_(Kyoto,_Japan).JPG</a></p>
<p>Or, use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seal_script" target="_blank">seal script</a>, mainly small seal script. As to looking formal and governmental, it may be the best choice. It's usually used for seals as its name says, but many military decorations also adopted this style, and the Japanese passport of today uses it too.<br />
<a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1931-34_China_Incident_War_Medal-003.JPG">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1931-34_China_Incident_War_Medal-003.JPG</a><br />
<a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1904-1905_Russo-Japanese_War_medal_reverse.jpg">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1904-1905_Russo-Japanese_War_medal_reverse.jpg</a><br />
<a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1931-34_China_Incident_War_Medal-002.JPG">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1931-34_China_Incident_War_Medal-002.JPG</a><br />
<a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:JapanpassportNew10y.PNG">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:JapanpassportNew10y.PNG</a><br />
with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clerical_script" target="_blank">clerical script</a>: <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Victory_medal_Japan_(revers)_crop.jpg">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Victory_medal_Japan_(revers)_crop.jpg</a><br />
seal-ish script: <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1939_Border_War_Medal_04.JPG">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1939_Border_War_Medal_04.JPG</a> <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Air_attack_of_Philippines_medal.jpg">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Air_attack_of_Philippines_medal.jpg</a></p>
<p>Plus, I prefer only 異 rather than putting both 異 and 常. It may be because somehow my browser is making the red circle look vertically stretched, however, and would possibly not look so terrible if it's a true circle. Of course this is just my aesthetic preference, so other Japanese speakers may have different opinions.</p>

							</div>

								
					
