			<div class="content" id="post-content-2861725">
									

<p>What do you mean 'cultural insensitivity'? This article didn't mangle the legend or stereotype Japanese culture or have racist writings or do anything that's actually culturally insensitive. What's wrong with writing about a popular Japanese myth? If anything, the authors are helping expand people's horizons by introducing them to the wonderful weirdness in Japanese mythology.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Seriously, when writing about Japan, don't just write about 妖怪, let alone popular or recognizable ones such as kappa or gashadokuro. I'm still waiting on an SCP about Futakichi-onna, the woman with two mouths; Nurikabe, a spirit acting as a wall misdirecting travelers at night; or Ashiarai Yashiki, a…giant foot that smashes through roofs and demands a washing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Then start writing them yourself instead of complaining that there aren't any.</p>

							</div>

								
					
